com.vector.cfg.model.access

Interface IReferrableAccess


  • @PublishedApi(value=ADDITIONS_ALLOWED)
 @ThreadSafe
public interface IReferrableAccess

    IReferrableAccess

    The IReferrableAccess is a basic model service which provides some general methods for dealing with MIReferrable objects (all types which have a shortname).

    Retrieving referrable objects

    Probably the most important methods in this service are
    • getAutosarPath(MIReferrable): Returns the AUTOSAR path of an object
    • getReferrableByPath(String): Searches an object by its AUTOSAR path
    • getReferrableByPath(MIARObject,String): Searches a child object by its relative AUTOSAR path below the specified parent object

    Shortname validation

    When client code creates new MIReferrable objects in the model, it is essential that their shortname is valid below the related parent. Duplicate shortnames are not allowed and lead to canceled model change transactions.
    • isValidShortname(MIARObject,String): Checks if the specified shortname is valid below the specified parent object. The method checks for example if this shortname already exists and if the contained characters are valid for shortnames
    • shortnameExists(MIARObject,String): Only checks if the shortname exists below the specified parent
    • getValidShortname(MIARObject,String,int): Creates a valid unused shortname by adding a numerical postfix string if the specified shortname already exists

    Post-build selectable issues:

    This is a ProjectService.

    This ProjectService is threadsafe

      • getAsrPath

        @PublishedMethod
AsrPath getAsrPath(com.vector.cfg.model.mdf.commoncore.autosar.MIReferrable obj)
        Returns the AUTOSAR path of the specified referrable or throws an IllegalStateException if an error occurs. Errors occur in the following cases:
        • The object is not member of the AUTOSAR model tree
        • The object or one of its parents doesn't have a shortname

        Remark: This method also works for invisible MDF objects (see the documentation of IModelAccess for details).

        Parameters:
        obj -
        Returns:
        Absolute AUTOSAR path of the object and never null
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if parameters are null
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - if another error occurred (e.g. if the object is not member of the model tree)

      • getValidShortname

        @PublishedMethod
java.lang.String getValidShortname(com.vector.cfg.model.mdf.commoncore.autosar.MIARObject parent,
                                                     java.lang.String name,
                                                     int numDigits)
        This method first checks if the specified shortname plus a potentially added number postfix is too long according to the AUTOSAR schema rules (128 characters max). If it is too long, a CRC32 of the original name is being calculated, the name is being truncated and the CRC32 is being added. The resulting name plus a potentially added postfix has exactly 128 characters.

        If the (potentially truncated) shortname does not exist below the specified parent it is returned without further changes. If it already exists, the method attaches an underscore followed by a number starting from 1. The number postfix is being increased as long as the resulting shortname exists. Finally a new non-existing shortname is returned.

        The numDigits parameter specifies the minimum number of digits to be attached. The attached number is prefixed by '0' to fill this length. If the finally found number is larger, it will not be cut to the specified number of digits - the number length is simply exceeded.

        Example: If the shortname "abc" already exists and 3 is specified as minimum number of digits, the method starts trying "abc_001". If the specified name already ends with a number sequence as specified above, the method returns the next unused one. The specified numDigits value will be ignored in this case and the actually found number of digits will be used.

        Example: If the shortname "abc_009" already exists, the method starts trying "abc_010".

        Parameters:
        parent -
        name - is a shortname to be checked and used as basis for attached numbers
        numDigits - is the number of digits, the attached number shall be formated with. If this value is 1 or lower, no leading '0' will be attached. If it is larger that 32, it will be set to 32.
        Returns:
        The created shortname or null if the specified shortname contains invalid characters

      • getValidShortnameForContainer

        @PublishedMethod
java.lang.String getValidShortnameForContainer(com.vector.cfg.model.mdf.commoncore.autosar.MIARObject parent,
                                                                 java.lang.String name,
                                                                 int numDigits,
                                                                 DefRef defRef)
        This method checks if the specified shortname exists below the specified parent or module-wide for SymbolicNameValue container. If not, the shortname is returned without changes. If it already exists, the method attaches an underscore followed by a number starting from 1. The number postfix is being increased as long as the resulting shortname exists. Finally a new non-existing shortname is returned.

        Remark: This method uses the same shortname truncation algorithm as getValidShortname(MIARObject, String, int)!

        Parameters:
        parent -
        name -
        numDigits -
        defRef - (EDefRefWildcard wildcard is supported)
        Returns:

      • isValidShortname

        @PublishedMethod
org.eclipse.core.runtime.IStatus isValidShortname(com.vector.cfg.model.mdf.commoncore.autosar.MIARObject parent,
                                                                    java.lang.String name)
        Checks if the specified short-name is valid below the specified parent object.

        The check fails if

        • At least one referrable child has the same name
        • The short-name contains invalid characters or is too long
        • The short-name is empty or doesn't exist
        • There is a removed derived sub-container with this name (see IDerivedContainerOperations)
        Parameters:
        parent -
        name -
        Returns:
        Check result and reason if failed (via getMessage())
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if parameters are null

      • isValidShortnameForContainer

        @PublishedMethod
org.eclipse.core.runtime.IStatus isValidShortnameForContainer(com.vector.cfg.model.mdf.commoncore.autosar.MIARObject parent,
                                                                                java.lang.String name,
                                                                                DefRef defRef)
        Returns true if the specified shortname is a valid shortname for a container below this parent but returns false in the following cases:
        • The shortname is empty or contains invalid characters.
        • The shortname already exists. Either below this parent or - if the definition is a symbolic name container definition - module-wide
        • The shortname is the name of a derived but deleted container - in case of a symbolic name container definition also module-wide
        This method is intended to be called before creating a new container to check if the specified name can really be used.
        Parameters:
        parent - the (existing) parent of the new child container
        name - the shortname to be checked
        defName - the definition of the new child container (EDefRefWildcard wildcard is supported)
        Returns:
